```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>
#include <sstream>

using namespace std;

int main() {
  int count = 0;
  ifstream file("file.txt");
  if (!file.is_open()) {
    cout << "Error opening file." << endl;
    return 1;
  }
  string line;
  while (getline(file, line)) {
    istringstream iss(line);
    for (string word : iss) {
      if (word == "your_specific_word") {
        count++;
      }
    }
  }
  file.close();
  cout << "The word 'your_specific_word' occurs " << count << " times in the file." << endl;
  return 0;
}
```

This program reads in a text file called "file.txt" line by line using the `getline()` function from the `<string>` library. It then uses an `istringstream` to split each line into individual words, and checks if each word is equal to the specific word you are looking for. If it is, the count is incremented.

You will need to replace "your_specific_word" with the actual word you want to search for in the file.

Once the program has finished reading through all the lines in the file, it closes the file and outputs the total number of occurrences of the specific word in the file.

